com.googlecode.cqengine.resultset.order

Class MaterializedOrderedResultSet<O>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.googlecode.cqengine.resultset.ResultSet<O>
      • com.googlecode.cqengine.resultset.common.WrappedResultSet<O>
        • com.googlecode.cqengine.resultset.order.MaterializedOrderedResultSet<O>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Closeable, AutoCloseable, Iterable<O>

    public class MaterializedOrderedResultSet<O>
extends WrappedResultSet<O>
    A ResultSet which wraps another ResultSet, providing an iterator() method which returns objects from the wrapped ResultSet in sorted order according to a comparator supplied to the constructor of this ResultSet, AND which implicitly deduplicates the objects returned as well.

    Note that the size() method does not necessarily reflect the outcome of that deduplication. As deduplication is expensive, the constructor accepts a boolean flag to specify if the size() method should perform deduplication.

    Deduplication is implemented by copying objects from the wrapped ResultSet into a sorted set on-demand when the iterator() method is called, and then returning an iterator over that set.

    Insertion-sorting, and then iterating objects in this manner has O(merge_cost^2 * log(merge_cost)) time complexity. See the iterator() and getMergeCost() methods for details.

    Author:
    Niall Gallagher

      • MaterializedOrderedResultSet

        public MaterializedOrderedResultSet(ResultSet<O> wrappedResultSet,
                                    Comparator<O> comparator,
                                    boolean deduplicateSize)
        Parameters:
        wrappedResultSet - The ResultSet to be ordered.
        comparator - The comparator to use for ordering
        deduplicateSize - If true, the size() method will deduplicate results such that the count it returns will match the number of objects returned by the iterator() method (but this deduplication is expensive); if false, the size() method will not deduplicate, and so the size reported might sometimes be greater then the number of objects which the iterator() method returns (but this computation is inexpensive).

      • iterator

        public Iterator<O> iterator()
        Builds an insertion-sorted set from the wrapped ResultSet, and returns an iterator over the sorted set.

        Time complexity for building an insertion sorted set is O(merge_cost * log(merge_cost)), and then iterating it makes this O(merge_cost^2 * log(merge_cost)). (Merge cost is an approximation of the cost of iterating all elements in any result set.)

      • size

        public int size()
        Returns the number of objects which would be returned by this ResultSet if iterated.

        Note that the cost of calling this method depends on the query for which it was constructed.

        For simple queries where a single query is supplied and a matching index exists, or where several such simple queries are supplied and are connected using a simple Or query, calculating the size via this method will be cheaper than iterating through the ResultSet and counting the number of objects individually.

        For more complex queries, where intersections must be performed or where no suitable indexes exist, calling this method can be non-trivial, but it will always be at least as cheap as iterating through the ResultSet and counting the number of objects individually.

        Note that whether or not this method deduplicates results is specified by the parameter supplied to the constructor of this ResultSet.

        Overrides:
        size in class WrappedResultSet<O>
        Returns:
        The number of objects which would be returned by this ResultSet if iterated
